        <!-- ══ SECTION 01 ══ -->
        <section class="guide-section" id="section-tracking" aria-labelledby="tracking-h">
          <span class="tag section-tag">01 — Ad Tracking</span>
          <h2 id="tracking-h">Shopify Conversion Tracking in 2026 — The Q1 ROAS Crisis and How to Fix It Free</h2>
          <p>If your Meta or Google ROAS dropped in Q1 2026, you are not alone — and the cause is more specific than "iOS tracking." Two separate events compounded into a tracking crisis for thousands of Shopify stores in the first weeks of January 2026.</p>

          <span id="section-q1crisis" style="display:block;height:80px;margin-top:-80px;visibility:hidden;"></span>
          <h3>What Actually Happened in Q1 2026 — The Two-Hit Combination</h3>
          <p>The first hit: <strong>iOS 26 stripped <code>fbclid</code> parameters from Private Browsing links, and from links shared via Mail and Messages</strong>. This is distinct from earlier iOS restrictions — it is not Safari's ITP throttling pixel fires, it is the click identifier itself being removed before the user even lands on your store. Without fbclid, Meta cannot attribute the click to an ad campaign, and your ROAS attribution becomes structurally broken for a meaningful segment of users.</p>
          <p>The second hit: <strong>Shopify changed App Pixels to "Optimised" mode on January 13 2026</strong>. This change silently throttled the data volume that third-party pixels receive from Shopify's checkout. Stores noticed ROAS declines in their dashboards but had no clear signal about why, because no error was thrown and no notification was sent.</p>

          <div class="impact-grid">
            <div class="impact-cell">
              <div class="ic-val" style="color:var(--rose);">iOS 26</div>
              <div class="ic-label">Hit 1</div>
              <div class="ic-desc">fbclid stripped from Private Browsing, Mail, and Messages links — attribution broken at click level</div>
            </div>
            <div class="impact-cell">
              <div class="ic-val" style="color:var(--amber);">Jan 13</div>
              <div class="ic-label">Hit 2</div>
              <div class="ic-desc">Shopify "Optimised" pixel mode throttles third-party app pixel data — silently, no error notification</div>
            </div>
            <div class="impact-cell">
              <div class="ic-val" style="color:var(--g);">CAPI Fix</div>
              <div class="ic-label">The Solution</div>
              <div class="ic-desc">Server-side tracking bypasses both — events sent direct from Shopify server, browser and pixel irrelevant</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>The combination means stores relying solely on browser pixels are now experiencing <strong>30–45% conversion data loss</strong> in 2026. The fix: server-side tracking via the Conversions API sends purchase events from Shopify's servers directly to Meta and Google, completely bypassing iOS restrictions, fbclid stripping, and the Optimised pixel throttle.</p>

          <div class="callout danger">
            <div class="callout-label">⚠ If your ROAS dropped in January 2026</div>
            <p>Check your Meta Events Manager → Data Sources. If your Event Match Quality dropped from "Good" to "Fair" around January 13 2026, the Shopify pixel change is the likely cause. <strong>CAPI Shield restores full event quality within 24 hours of deployment.</strong> See the <a href={`${SITE}/blog/shopify-meta-roas-dropped-2026-fix`}>Q1 2026 ROAS fix guide</a> for the full diagnosis.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="stat-callout">
            <div class="sc-val">40%</div>
            <div class="sc-body">
              <p><strong>Average conversion data loss</strong> for Shopify stores relying solely on browser pixels in Q1 2026. A store spending $10,000/month on Meta Ads is effectively making bidding decisions based on 60% of its actual conversion data — leaving smart bidding algorithms systematically underpowered.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>The knock-on effects compound quickly. Meta's Advantage+ and Google's Smart Bidding both rely on conversion signals to optimise ad delivery. When those signals are incomplete, your campaigns bid on audiences that look like your visible converters — missing the percentage you cannot see.</p>

          <h3>What Server-Side Tracking Is and Why It Solves This</h3>
          <p>Server-side tracking sends the conversion event directly from Shopify's servers to the ad platform's API. The browser is not involved. iOS has no opportunity to interfere. The "Optimised" pixel throttle is irrelevant because you are not using App Pixels at all.</p>
          <p>The technical architecture: when a customer completes a purchase, Shopify fires a webhook to Make.com. Make.com receives the event, enriches it with the order data, and forwards it to Meta's Conversions API and Google's Enhanced Conversions endpoint simultaneously.</p>

          <div class="callout info">
            <div class="callout-label">Case Study — Verified</div>
            <p>A Shopify apparel store spending £42,000/month on Meta Ads implemented CAPI Shield in January 2026. Within 30 days, reported purchase events increased by 31%. The store recovered £8,200/month in previously invisible revenue — without increasing budget. Reported ROAS improved from 2.1x to 2.9x.</p>
          </div>

          <span id="section-capi" style="display:block;height:80px;margin-top:-80px;visibility:hidden;"></span>
          <h3>How to Deploy CAPI Shield — Step by Step</h3>
          <p>CAPI Shield connects Shopify to Make.com via a webhook, then routes purchase events to Meta's Conversions API and Google's Enhanced Conversions. The entire setup takes six minutes and requires zero code.</p>

          <div class="step-cards" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/HowTo">
            <meta itemprop="name" content="How to deploy CAPI Shield server-side tracking for Shopify" />
