          <h2 id="stability-h">Google Apps Script Quota Errors — Why Your Automation Breaks Mid-Month and How to Fix It</h2>
          <p>If you use Google Apps Script for any part of your Shopify automation — document generation, spreadsheet triggers, inventory calculations, email dispatch — you have probably encountered execution quota errors. Your workflow stops, data is not processed, and you may not know it happened until you discover a gap in your inventory ledger.</p>
          <p>Google Apps Script enforces hard limits on free accounts: <a href={`${SITE}/blog/google-apps-script-quotas-explained-how-to-avoid-limits-and-scale-your-automations`}>6 minutes per script execution, 90 minutes of total execution time per day</a>, and quotas on specific services like Gmail (100 emails per day), Sheets, and UrlFetch.</p>

          <div class="stat-callout">
            <div class="sc-val">6 min</div>
            <div class="sc-body">
              <p><strong>Maximum single execution time</strong> for Google Apps Script on free accounts. A store processing bulk orders or running a complex spreadsheet calculation can easily hit this limit during a busy period — silently breaking automations exactly when order volume is highest.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="callout info">
            <div class="callout-label">High-volume stores · 500+ orders/month</div>
            <p>Scaling past 500 orders/month? Gmail API limits will break your automations. <strong>Google Workspace removes every Gmail API limit</strong> and keeps your entire $0 stack running at full speed during traffic spikes and Black Friday volumes. <a href="https://referworkspace.app.goo.gl/sy2C" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored">Activate Google Workspace free trial →</a></p>
          </div>

          <h3>The Autocrat Quota Fix — What It Does</h3>
          <p>Autocrat Quota Fix is a set of architectural patterns that restructure how your Google Apps Script workflows handle high-volume execution. The three core techniques are chunked processing, exponential backoff, and state persistence.</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Chunked processing</strong> — instead of processing all pending rows in a single run, the script processes a configurable batch size (typically 50–100 rows) per execution, then reschedules itself.</li>
            <li><strong>Exponential backoff</strong> — when a service quota error is encountered, the script pauses with an exponentially increasing delay before retrying. Most transient quota errors resolve within 2–3 retry cycles.</li>
            <li><strong>State persistence</strong> — the script stores its current processing position in a Script Property, so if an execution is interrupted it resumes from exactly where it stopped.</li>
          </ul>

